cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.CC, cs.DS 

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper proposes a technique to design LDPC codes with good performance in both the waterfall and the error floor region over the binary-input AWGN channel. This falls under the scope of information theory. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The proposed construction results in quasi-cyclic codes which are attractive in practice due to simple encoder and decoder implementation. This is relevant to networking and internet architecture. 
3. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper mentions the Tanner graph of the code, which is a graphical representation of the code's structure. This is relevant to social and information networks. 
4. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper discusses the design process of the code, which involves maximizing the components of the ACE spectrum in a greedy fashion. This may involve computational complexity considerations. 
5. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The proposed technique involves lifting a protograph cyclically to a certain block length of interest. This may involve data structures and algorithms.
